{{Infobox person |name=Aimen Dean |image= |image_size= |caption= | other_names = Ramzi | birth_date= | birth_place = Saudi Arabia | death_date = | death_place = | children = | occupation = }}
'''Aimen Dean''' ({{lang-ar|ایمن دین}}), better known as '''Ramzi''' ({{lang|ar|رمزی}}) is a [[Bahrainian]] man who was a founding member<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/62771/mi5-double-agent-offers-rare-insight-into-al-qaeda-and-jihad | title=MI5 double agent offers rare insight into al-Qaeda and jihad | publisher=theweek | accessdate= }}</ref> of [[al-Qaeda]]. In 1998, he joined the [[Secret Intelligence Service]] and became an [[MI6]] spy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-31700894|title=The spy who came in from al-Qaeda|date=2015-03-03|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-12-23|language=en-GB}}</ref>
==Early life== Dean was born in Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11447999/Aimen-Dean-al-Qaeda-review.html | title=Aimen Dean's al-Qaeda story: dramatic but hard to swallow | publisher=telegraph | accessdate= }}</ref> By the age of 12 he had memorised the Quran and become a [[Hafiz (Quran)|Hafiz]]. Following the death of his mother he sought solace in [[Sayyid Qutb]]'s [[Fi Zilal al-Quran|In the Shade of the Koran]]. He was part of an Islamic Awareness circle at [[Omar Bin Abdulaziz Mosque]] in [[Khobar]], where one of the instructors was [[Yusef al-Ayeri]]. In 1989 his eldest brother Moheddin went to fight in Afghanistan for 3 months. At 15 he travelled to Bosnia to participate in the [[Bosnian War]] with a friend from the circle [[Khaled Ali Hajj]] who had returned from fighting in Afghanistan. In Bosnia he was part of the [[Bosnian mujahideen]] Brigade who massacred over 200 prisoners by decapitation following the [[Battle for Vozuća]]. He witnessed his friend Khaled saw off the head of a prisoner with a serrated hunting knife. Just before the end of the war he was recruited by [[Khalid Sheikh Mohammed]] who suggested that he go to Afghanistan and give him a contact in Peshawar, Pakistan. <ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=opNNDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT2&source=gbs_selected_pages&cad=2#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=Nine Lives: My time as the West's top spy inside al-Qaeda | publisher=Oneworld Publications | accessdate= }}</ref>
==Al-Qaeda== Following Bosnia, Dean was invited to [[Kandahar]] to swear allegiance to [[Osama bin Laden]] and join [[al-Qaeda]]. In Afghanistan he trained al-Qaeda recruits in the basics of Islamic theology, history and the essentials of religious practice. He was worried by the [[1998 United States embassy bombings]] and asked [[Abdullah al-Mohaja]] for the religious justification. He was pointed to a 13th Century [[Fatwa]] by [[Ibn Taymiyyah]]. He researched the [[Fatwa]] which was about the Mongol invasion and their use of human shields when besieging cities<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.islamweb.net/emainpage/index.php?page=showfatwa&Option=FatwaId&Id=170403 | title=Attacking the disbelievers if they use Muslims as human shields | publisher=Islamweb | accessdate= }}</ref>, it was clear to him that this was no justification for killing civilian bystanders. He believes the concept of Jihad is changed by al-Qaeda. The target of Jihad in al-Qaeda is starting world war opposed to the West.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.tasnimnews.com/fa/news/1396/02/23/1405115/%D8%AE%D8%A7%D8%B7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D9%86%D9%81%D9%88%D8%B0%DB%8C-mi6-%D8%AF%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%A7%D8%B9%D8%AF%D9%87 | title=The memories of Aimen Dean | publisher=tasnimnews | accessdate= }}</ref>
==Spying== Dean decided to leave al-Qaeda going to [[Qatar]] on the pretext of his health with the intention to disappear. He was captured on arrival in Qatar by Qatari Intelligence, who gave him a choice of intelligence agency and he choose to work with MI6. MI6 then spent 7 months debriefing him. At the end of the debriefing in agreed to go back to Afghanistan as a spy.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
Dean then spied on al-Qaeda for 8 years prior to being exposed by Washington. During this time he travelled between Afghanistan and London on behalf of al-Qaeda allowing him to report to MI6, when in the UK he acted as al-Qaeda's representative and had to be careful to preach and recruit with in UK law.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/62771/mi5-double-agent-offers-rare-insight-into-al-qaeda-and-jihad | title=MI5 double agent offers rare insight into al-Qaeda and jihad | publisher=theweek | accessdate= }}</ref> <ref>{{cite web | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/23/world/csr-al-qaeda-spy/index.html | title=A Former Spy Inside Al Qaeda Speaks | publisher=CNN | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://cnnpressroom.blogs.cnn.com/2018/05/22/cnn-special-report-a-double-life-the-spy-inside-al-qaeda-with-christiane-amanpour/ | title=A Double Life: The Spy Inside Al Qaeda with Christiane Amanpour | publisher=CNN | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-31700894 | title=The spy who came in from al-Qaeda | publisher=BBC | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/al-qaeda-double-agent-how-aimen-dean-went-from-working-for-osama-bin-laden-to-mi6-superspy-7nhk3pkrm | title=The al-Qaeda superspy: how Aimen Dean went from making bombs for Osama bin Laden to working for MI6 | publisher=The Times | accessdate= }}</ref>
Dean's cover was blown by a US writer who using CIA sources disclosed his identity with details that could only be sourced to him in a book.{{cn|date=June 2018}}
==Later career== After being exposed, Dean started a career as a speaker and security consultant.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/on-the-middle-east/2015/jun/05/former-al-qaida-spy-for-mi6-urges-effort-to-confuse-islamic-state | title=Al-Qaida fighter turned MI6 spy urges effort to 'confuse' Islamic State | publisher=The Guardian | accessdate= }}</ref>
Dean is the author of two books: * ''The Eternal Bridge Over the River Innocence'': A novel about the story of what happens to young bright and decent [[Muslims]] who come under radical influence.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/the-times/i-was-mi6s-spy-in-alqaida/news-story/329102f5d0f2feee0a77f32b9f0d9e80 | title=I was MI6'S spy in al-Qa'ida | publisher=The Australian | accessdate= }}</ref> * ''Nine Lives: My Time As Mi6's Top Spy Inside Al-qaeda'': biography of his life as a spy inside [[al-Qaeda]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://chicago.cbslocal.com/2018/05/24/former-spy-inside-al-qaeda-speaks/ | title=A Former Spy Inside Al Qaeda Speaks | publisher=CBS Chicargo | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/23/world/csr-al-qaeda-spy/index.html | title=A Former Spy Inside Al Qaeda Speaks | publisher=CNN | accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://cnnpressroom.blogs.cnn.com/2018/05/22/cnn-special-report-a-double-life-the-spy-inside-al-qaeda-with-christiane-amanpour/ | title=A Double Life: The Spy Inside Al Qaeda with Christiane Amanpour | publisher=CNN | accessdate= }}</ref>
