[[Pedro II of Brazil]] was the second and last emperor of [[Brazil]]. Despite his popularity among Brazilians, Pedro II was removed from his throne in 1889 after a 58-year reign. He was promptly exiled with his family. Despite his deposition, he did not make an attempt to regain power. He died in 1891 while in Paris, France, after two years in exile. 

== Exile ==
[[File:La Revolution au Brésil. — Débarquement de Dom Pedro, a Lisbonne. — Le canot impérial abordant a l'Arsenal de la Marine.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Landing of Dom Pedro on [[Lisbon]]: The imperial boat approaching the Navy's Arsenal.]]
[[File:Família Imperial por Otto Hees.jpg|thumb|left|200px|The last photograph of the Brazilian imperial family, 1889]]

The monarchist reaction after the [[Decline and fall of Pedro II of Brazil#Republican coup|fall of the empire]] "was not small, and even less so its repression."{{sfn|Salles|1996|p=194}} The "new regime suppressed with swift brutality and total disdain for civil liberties all attempts to launch a monarchist party or to publish monarchist newspapers."{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=400}} Soon after several popular riots in protest against the coup occurred as well as battles between monarchist Army troops and republican militias.{{sfn|Mônaco Janotti|1986|p=117}} Those were followed by a civil war in which monarchist military and politicians tried to restore the empire in the [[Federalist Riograndense Revolution (Brazil)|Federalist Revolution]] and the [[Revolta da Armada|Second Navy Rebellion]].{{sfn|Martins|2008|p=116}}{{sfn|Salles|1996|p=195}} The last monarchist rebellion occurred in 1904, in what was called the [[Vaccine Revolt]].{{sfn|Salles|1996|p=195}}{{sfn|Mônaco Janotti|1986|p=255}}

=== Death ===
On 23 November 1891, Pedro II appeared at the [[French Academy of Sciences]] for the last time to participate in an election.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=238}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=26}} The following morning, he dispassionately noted in his diary the news that the dictator [[Deodoro da Fonseca]] had resigned: "10:30. Deodoro has quit."{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=28}} He soon afterwards took a long drive in an open carriage along the [[Seine]], even though it was a very cold day. He felt ill after returning to the Hôtel de Bedford that evening.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=238}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=27}} The illness progressed into [[pneumonia]] during the following days.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=238}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=29}} There was no celebration of his birthday on 2 December, with the exception of a simple mass said while he remained in bed. At that time [[Isabel, Princess Imperial of Brazil|his daughter Isabel]], [[Gaston, comte d'Eu|his son-in-law Gaston]] and his grandchildren were in attendance.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=29}}{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|pp=238–9}}{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=489}} However, he later received several French and Brazilian visitors who had come to offer birthday congratulations.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=29}}

[[File:Pedro II 1891 00.jpg|thumb|left|280px|Pedro II, dressed with the uniform of [[Marshal (Brazil)#Marshals of the Empire of Brazil|Marshal of the Army]] lying in state, 6 December 1891. Notice the book under his head.]]

His health suddenly worsened on the morning of 3 December.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=30}} Other relatives and friends went to see him once news of the seriousness of the situation began to spread. On 4 December, he received the last sacrament from Abbé [[Pierre-Jacques-Almeyre Le Rébours]], [[Curate|curé]] of [[Église de la Madeleine|La Madeleine]].{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1891}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=601}} That night Pedro II began declining, and died at 12:35&nbsp;am on 5 December.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|pp=238–9}}{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=489}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1892}} His last words were, "May God grant me these last wishes&nbsp;– peace and prosperity for Brazil..."{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=30}} He was so weakened that he suffered no pain.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=601}} Pedro II was surrounded by his daughter Isabel, the Count of Eu, his grandchildren ([[Pedro de Alcântara, Prince of Grão Para|Pedro]], [[Prince Luís of Orléans-Braganza (1878–1920)|Luís]], [[Prince Antônio Gastão of Orléans-Braganza|Antonio]], [[Prince Peter of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Pedro Augusto]] and [[Prince August Leopold of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha|Augusto Leopoldo]]), his sisters [[Januária Maria, Princess Imperial of Brazil|Januária]] and [[Princess Francisca of Brazil|Francisca]] with their husbands (respectively the [[Prince Louis, Count of Aquila|Count of Aquila]] and the [[François d'Orléans, prince de Joinville|Prince of Joinville]]).{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 3|p=165}}

According to the [[death certificate]] the ''causa mortis'' was acute pneumonia in the left lung.{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=489}}{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=602}} Pedro II died without abdicating, and Isabel inherited the claim to the throne of the Brazilian Empire.{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=489}} She solemnly kissed her father's hands, and after that, all those present, including dozens of Brazilians already there kissed her hand, recognizing her as the Empress ''de jure'' of Brazil.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1892}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=602}} The [[Baron of Rio Branco]], who was also present, later wrote: "The Brazilians, thirty and something, went in line and, one by one, sprinkled holy water on the corpse and kissed his hand. I did the same. They were saying farewell to the great dead."{{sfn|Lyra 1977, Vol 3|p=165}} Senator [[Gaspar da Silveira Martins]] arrived soon after the Emperor's death and, when he saw the body of his old friend, wept convulsively.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=605}}

Isabel declined an autopsy, which allowed the body to be embalmed at 9&nbsp;am on 5 December. Six liters of [[hydrochloride]] of zinc and aluminum was injected into his [[common carotid artery]].{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=603}} A [[death mask]] was also made.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=605}} Pedro II was attired in the court dress uniform of a [[Marshal (Brazil)#Marshals of the Empire of Brazil|Marshal of the Army]] to represent his position as commander-in-chief of the Brazilian armed forces.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=603}} On his chest were placed the [[Order of the Southern Cross]], the [[Order of the Golden Fleece]] and the [[Order of the Rose]]. His hands held a silver crucifix sent by [[Pope Leo XIII]]. Two Brazilian flags covered his legs.{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=489}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=603}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1893}} While the body was being prepared, the Count of Eu found a sealed package in the room, and next to it a message written by the Emperor himself: "It is soil from my country, I wish it to be placed in my coffin in case I die away from my fatherland."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=489}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1897}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=604}} The package, which contained soil from every Brazilian province, was duly placed inside the coffin.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1897}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=606}} Three coffins were used: an inner coffin of lead lined with white satin which contained the body, and two outer coffins (one of varnished oak and the other of oak covered by black velvet).{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=606}}

=== Funeral ===

[[File:Hans Meyer - Funérailles de l'empereur du Brésil, 1891.jpg|thumb|300px|Funeral of Pedro II of Brazil depicted at the cover of the ''[[Le Petit Journal (newspaper)|Le Petit Journal]]'' (by [[Hans Meyer (artist)|Hans Meyer]]).]]

In the hours following the death of Pedro II, thousands of people came to the Hôtel de Bedford. Among these were the [[Prime Minister of France|President of the Council of Ministers]], [[Charles de Freycinet]], and the ministers of War and the Navy.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=605}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1893}} In a single day, more than 2,000 telegrams were received by the hotel with messages of condolence.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=606}} French president [[Marie François Sadi Carnot|Sadi Carnot]] was traveling in the south of the country and sent the members of the Military Household to pay homage to the deceased monarch on his behalf.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=607}} Princess Isabel wished to hold a discrete and private burial ceremony.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=609}} However, she eventually accepted the French Government's request for a [[State funeral|Head of State's funeral]]. To prevent political disruption,{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=613}} the government decided that the burial would be officially accorded because the Emperor was a recipient of the Grand Cross of the [[Légion d'honneur]],{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1896}} although with the pomp due to a monarch.{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=489}} Requests from Brazil's republican government to deny an official funeral and any public display of the imperial flag were ignored by the French government.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=613}}

The coffin which contained the body of Pedro II departed the Hôtel de Bedford for [[Église de la Madeleine|La Madeleine]] on the evening of 8 December.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=615}} Eight French soldiers bore the coffin, which was covered with the imperial flag.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=615}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1899}} A crowd of more than 5,000 people was on hand to witness the cortege.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=615}} The hearse was the same one used for the funerals of Cardinal [[François-Nicholas-Madeleine Morlot|Morlot]], the [[Charles Auguste Louis Joseph, duc de Morny|duc de Morny]] and [[Adolphe Thiers]].{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1899}}

[[File:Funeral Pedro II 1891.jpg|thumb|250px|Pedro II's coffin leaving the [[Église de la Madeleine|Church of Madeleine]], 1891.]]

On the following day, thousands of mourners attended the ceremony at La Madeleine. Aside from Pedro II's family, these included: [[Amadeo of Spain|Amadeo of Savoy]], former king of Spain; [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]], former king of the Two Sicilies; [[Isabella II of Spain|Isabella II]], former queen of Spain; [[Philippe, comte de Paris]]; and other members of European royalty.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1898}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=617}} Also present were General [[Joseph Brugère]], representing President Sadi Carnot; the presidents of the [[Senate of France|Senate]] and the [[Chamber of Deputies of France|Chamber of Deputies]]{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}} as well as their members; diplomats; and other representatives of the French government.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=618}} Nearly all members of the [[Académie française|French Academy]], the [[Académie des Inscriptions et Belles-Lettres]], the [[French Academy of Sciences]], the [[Académie des Beaux-Arts]] and the [[Académie des Sciences Morales et Politiques]] were in attendance.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1899}} Also among those present were [[Eça de Queiroz]],{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}} [[Alexandre Dumas, fils]], [[Gabriel Auguste Daubrée]], [[Jules Arsène Arnaud Claretie]], [[Marcellin Berthelot]], [[Jean Louis Armand de Quatrefages de Bréau]], [[Edmond Jurien de la Gravière]], [[Julius Oppert]], [[Camille Doucet]], and many other notable personages.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1899}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1898}} Other governments from the Americans and Europe also sent representatives, as did distant countries such as [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turkey]], [[Qing Dynasty|China]], [[Empire of Japan|Japan]] and [[Persia under Qajar dynasty|Persia]].{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=618}} Notably absent was any delegation from Brazil.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}}

[[File:Paris. — Funeráilles de Dom Pedro II, Empereur de Brésil. — (Dessin d'après nature, de M. Charles Morel.).jpg|thumb|300px|Funeral of Pedro II, Emperor of Brazil, in [[Paris]] (by [[Charles Morel]], published at [[L'Univers illustré|''L'Univers illustré: journal hebdomadaire'']], Levy (Paris), nº 1.917, 19/12/1891).]]

Following the services, the coffin was taken in procession to the train station, from whence it would travel to [[Portugal]]. Between 200,000{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=239}} and 300,000{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}} people lined the route despite incessant rain and cold temperatures.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=614}} Some 80,000 French military troops marched in the procession.{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=620}} Two carriages carried almost 200 funeral [[wreaths]] which bore messages paying homage to the Emperor such as: "To Dom Pedro, [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria R.I.]]",{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}} "To the great Emperor for whom [[Luís Alves de Lima e Silva|Caxias]], [[Manuel Luís Osório, Marquis of Erval|Osório]], Andrade Neves and many other heroes fought, Fatherland Volunteers from [[Rio de Janeiro (state)|Rio de Janeiro]]",{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}}{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=619}} "A group of Brazilian students in Paris",{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}} "Happy times when the thought, the word and the pen were free, when Brazil freed oppressed people…" (sent by the Baron of Ladário, [[Marquis of Tamandaré]], Viscount of Sinimbu, Rodolfo Dantas, [[Joaquim Nabuco]] and [[Alfredo d'Escragnolle Taunay|Taunay]]),{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}} "To the great Brazilian worthy of honors from the Fatherland and Humanity. ''Ubique Patria Memor''."{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}} (sent by the [[Baron of Rio Branco]]),{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=604}} "From the people of [[Rio Grande do Sul]] to the liberal and patriotic king",{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}} and "A [[Afro-Brazilian|Brazilian black]] on behalf of his race".{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1900}} The "state funeral granted by the French republic proclaimed the former’s [Pedro II] personal virtues and popularity and, by implication, distinguished the imperial regime from other monarchies."{{sfn|Barman|1999|p=401}}

All along the route, from France, through Spain and finally into Portugal, people paid homage to Pedro II. But still no representative appeared on behalf of Brazil's republican government.{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=240}} The journey continued on to the [[Monastery of São Vicente de Fora|Church of São Vicente de Fora]] near [[Lisbon]], where the body of Pedro II was interred in the [[Monastery of São Vicente de Fora#Braganza Pantheon|Braganza Pantheon]] on 12 December. His tomb rested between that of his stepmother [[Amélie of Leuchtenberg|Amélia]] and that of his wife [[Teresa Cristina of the Two Sicilies|Teresa Cristina]].{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=240}}{{sfn|Calmon|1975|pp=1900–2}}

=== Death's repercussions ===

The Brazilian republican government, "fearful of a backlash resulting from the death of the emperor," banned any official reaction.{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=493}} Nevertheless, the [[Brazilian people]] were far from indifferent to Pedro II's demise, and the "repercussions in Brazil were also immense, despite the government's effort to suppress. There were demonstrations of sorrow throughout the country: shuttered business activity, flags displayed at half-staff, black armbands on clothes, death knells, religious ceremonies."{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=240}}{{sfn|Mônaco Janotti|1986|p=50}} An article written by João Mendes de Almeida on 7 December 1891 says that, "The news of the death of His Majesty Emperor Dom Pedro II has revealed the feelings of the Brazilian nation towards the Imperial dynasty. The consternation has been general."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=495}} Solemn "masses were held all over the country, which were followed by eulogies praising Dom Pedro II and the monarchy".{{sfn|Mônaco Janotti|1986|p=50}} So, the "Republic stood by silently, given the strength and impact of reactions."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=493}}

[[File:Funeral pedro II Lisboa 1891.jpg|thumb|250px|Pedro II's coffin arriving in Lisbon, 1891.]]

Police were sent to suppress public demonstrations of sorrow, "provoking serious incidents", although "the people were in sympathy with these manifestants."{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=610}} A popular gathering in memory of the deceased emperor occurred on 9 December and was organized by the Marquis of Tamandaré, Viscount of Ouro Preto, Viscount of Sinimbu, Baron of Ladário, Carlos de Laet, Alfredo d' Escragnolle Taunay, Rodolfo Dantas, Afonso Celso and Joaquim Nabuco.{{sfn|Calmon|1975|p=1907}} Even old political adversaries of Pedro II praised him, "criticizing his policies" but pointing out "his patriotism, honesty, abnegation, spirit of justice, devotion to work, tolerance and simplicity."{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=241}} [[Quintino Bocaiúva]], one of the main republican leaders, spoke: "The entire world, it may be said, has paid homage which Mr. Dom Pedro de Alcântara has earned through his virtues as a great citizen."{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=240}} Some "members of republican clubs protested against what they characterized as exaggerated sentimentalism in the tributes, seeing in these monarchist maneuvers. They were lonely voices."{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|p=240}}

Foreign reaction also revealed sympathy towards the monarch. ''[[The New York Times]]'' on 5 December praised Pedro II, considering him "the most enlightened monarch of the century" and also stating that "he made Brazil as free as a monarchy could be."{{sfn|Carvalho|2007|pp=240–1}} The ''[[New York Herald|Herald]]'' wrote: "In another time, and in happier circumstances, he would be worshiped and honored by his subjects and would be known in history as 'Dom Pedro the Good'."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=491}} ''[[New York Tribune|The Tribune]]'' affirmed that his "reign was serene, peaceable and prosperous."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=491}} ''[[The Times]]'' observed, in a long article, "Until November 1889, it was believed that the deceased Emperor and his wife were unanimously beloved in Brazil due to his intellectual and moral qualities and by his affectionate interest for the well-being of his subjects [...] When in Rio de Janeiro he was constantly seen in public; and two times per week he met his subjects, as well as foreign travelers, captivating all with his courtesy."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=491}}

''The Weekly Register'' wrote, "He looked more like a poet or a scholar than an emperor, but had he had been given the chance to materialize his several projects, without a doubt he would have made Brazil one of the richest countries in the [[New World]]."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|pp=491–2}} The French periodical ''Le Jour'' affirmed that "he was effectively the first sovereign that, following [[Franco-Prussian War|our disaster of 1871]], dared to visit us. Our defeat did not move him away from us. France will know how to be grateful."{{sfn|Besouchet|1993|p=609}} ''The Globe'' also wrote that he "was well learned, he was patriotic; he was gentle and indulgent; he had all the private virtues, as well as the public ones, and died in exile."{{sfn|Schwarcz|1998|p=492}}

