{{Infobox officeholder | honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]] | name = René Cormier | honorific-suffix = | image = | imagesize = | office = [[Senate of Canada|Senator]] for [[New Brunswick]] | appointed = David Johnston | nominator = [[Justin Trudeau]] | predecessor = | successor = | term_start = November 10, 2016 | term_end = | birth_date = April 27, 1956 | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | spouse = | party = [[Independent Senators Group]] | relations = | children = | residence = | alma_mater = | occupation = | profession = Artist | cabinet = | committees = | portfolio = | religion = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }} '''René Cormier''' (born April 27, 1956) is a Canadian [[Acadians|Acadian]] artist and activist from [[New Brunswick]]. On October 27, 2016, Cormier was named to the [[Senate of Canada]] by Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] to sit as an [[Independent politician|independent]].<ref name="Oct 2016 Senate appointment">{{cite news | access-date=October 27, 2016 | url=http://globalnews.ca/news/3028500/justin-trudeau-set-to-name-nine-new-senate-appointments/ | title=Justin Trudeau set to name nine new senate appointments | work=[[Global News]] | date=October 27, 2016 | agency=[[The Canadian Press]] | last=Bryden | first=Joan}}</ref><ref name=ici>{{cite news|title=René Cormier sera sénateur|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/regions/atlantique/2016/10/27/003-acadie-rene-cormier-senat-canadien.shtml|accessdate=27 October 2016|work=ICI.Radio-Canada.ca|agency=The Canadian Press|language=fr-ca}}</ref> Cormier assumed his seat on November 10, 2016.
A [[French Canadians|Francophone]], he is president of the {{Interlanguage link multi|Société nationale de l'Acadie|fr}} (SNA), the primary organization championing Acadian artists. Following his appointment to the Senate, Cormier stated that he plans to continue with his work with the SNA, while avoiding any conflicts of interest.<ref name=ici/> He formerly served as president for the [[Commission internationale du theatre francophone]], director of the {{Interlanguage link multi|Théâtre populaire d'Acadie|fr}}, president of the {{Interlanguage link multi|Fédération culturelle canadienne-française|fr}}, and as a member of the board for the [[Canadian Conference of the Arts]].<ref name="Oct 2016 Senate appointment" />
